{"timestamp": "2025-12-12 04:08:44.209670", "event": "llm_end", "text": "**What the data shows**\n\nAll of the ping tests succeeded – every packet was received (rx = 2 for every tx = 2).  \nThere is no packet loss anywhere in the network.\n\nThe only thing that stands out is the **high round‑trip times** for a handful of hosts.  \nFor example:\n\n| Source | Destination | Avg RTT (ms) | Notes |\n|--------|-------------|--------------|-------|\n| pc_0_0 | pc_1_4 | 5.5 | 5 ms is higher than the typical 2–3 ms seen elsewhere |\n| pc_2_4 | pc_1_4 | 6.3 | 6 ms is noticeably higher |\n| pc_1_3 | pc_3_1 | 3.8 | 3.8 ms is higher than the 2 ms seen for most other paths |\n| pc_1_6 | pc_3_1 | 5.1 | 5 ms is higher |\n| pc_3_6 | pc_1_4 | 4.3 | 4 ms is higher |\n\nAll other paths are in the 2–4 ms range, which is what you would expect for a local‑area network with a single hop between the two PCs.\n\n**Likely cause**\n\nThe high RTTs are almost certainly caused by a **sub‑optimal routing path** – the traffic is being sent through an extra hop (or a slower link) that is not needed.  \nIn a typical campus‑style topology this can happen when:\n\n* A router or switch is mis‑configured and is forwarding traffic through a longer path.\n* A VLAN or routing table entry is wrong, causing traffic to be sent to a different switch or router.\n* A link is overloaded or has a higher latency (e.g., a 100 Mbps link instead of 1 Gbps).\n\nBecause the ping results show no loss, the network is still functional; the problem is only a **performance degradation**.\n\n**Suggested fix**\n\n1. **Identify the path**  \n   Run a traceroute (or `tracert` on Windows) from the affected PCs to the destination.  \n   Example:  \n   ```bash\n   ping -c 2 pc_1_4\n   traceroute pc_1_4\n   ```\n   Look for an extra hop or a hop that is on a different VLAN or router than the rest of the traffic.\n\n2. **Check routing tables**  \n   On the routers/switches that sit between the two PCs, verify that the routing table for the subnet of the destination is correct.  \n   ```bash\n   show ip route 10.1.4.0/24\n   show ip route 10.3.1.0/24\n   ```\n   If a route is pointing to a slower interface or a different next‑hop, correct it.\n\n3. **Verify VLAN and interface configuration**  \n   Ensure that the interfaces connecting the two PCs are on the same VLAN and that the link speed is set to 1 Gbps (or the maximum available).  \n   ```bash\n   show interfaces status\n   show interfaces switchport\n   ```\n\n4. **Re‑apply the correct route**  \n   If a wrong route was found, delete it and add the correct one.  \n   ```bash\n   no ip route 10.1.4.0 255.255.255.0 <wrong-next-hop>\n   ip route 10.1.4.0 255.255.255.0 <correct-next-hop>\n   ```\n\n5. **Test again**  \n   After making the change, run the ping test again. The RTTs should drop to the normal 2–3 ms range.\n\n**Bottom line**\n\nThe network is not broken – it’s just routing traffic through a longer, slower path for a few hosts.  \nFixing the routing/VLAN configuration to use the shortest, fastest path will bring the latency back to normal.", "generation_info": {"model": "gpt-oss:20b", "created_at": "2025-12-12T04:08:43.427950151Z", "done": true, "done_reason": "stop", "total_duration": 32521543108, "load_duration": 68771133, "prompt_eval_count": 8192, "prompt_eval_duration": 7361899174, "eval_count": 2606, "eval_duration": 25063609021, "model_name": "gpt-oss:20b"}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8192, "output_tokens": 2606, "total_tokens": 10798}}
